1
00:00:01,921 --> 00:00:20,082
Foundation Course 1, Talk 4 The Second Noble Truth The Cause of Suffering, Desire The Second Noble Truth was formulated by the Buddha in his first ever discourse after his enlightenment as Isipatana Park near Benares on the Ganges River.

2
00:00:21,664 --> 00:00:24,626
It's called The Discourse on the Turning of the Wheel of the Law.

3
00:00:26,489 --> 00:00:30,814
This, O disciples, is the Noble Truth of the Cause of Suffering.

4
00:00:31,199 --> 00:00:45,277
That craving which leads to rebirth, combined with pleasure and passion, finding satisfaction now here, now there, namely, the craving for sense pleasure, the craving for new existence, and the craving for annihilation.

5
00:00:47,521 --> 00:00:53,950
So the cause of our suffering, or unsatisfactoriness in our lives, is desire or craving for sensual pleasure.

6
00:00:54,722 --> 00:01:01,411
To understand why this is, we need to go down one step further and ask why it is that we desire in the first place.

7
00:01:02,993 --> 00:01:08,019
According to the Buddha, our fundamental, call it existential position, is that we are ignorant.

8
00:01:09,102 --> 00:01:12,286
This ignorance is not stupidity or blameworthy lack of education.

9
00:01:12,986 --> 00:01:15,909
This ignorance means the same as the root meaning in English.

10
00:01:17,432 --> 00:01:18,013
NOT KNOWING

11
00:01:20,203 --> 00:01:21,105
we simply don't know.

12
00:01:22,105 --> 00:01:23,126
And what is it we don't know?

13
00:01:23,828 --> 00:01:26,370
It is the cause of our suffering and how to put an end to it.

14
00:01:27,352 --> 00:01:42,447
Because we're ignorant of this, this ignorant mind which doesn't know seems to find an answer and since the answer is based on wrong understanding, sometimes even guess or fantasy, for the real truth of the matter is hidden, delusion is produced in the mind.

15
00:01:43,268 --> 00:01:46,370
This delusion is the active side of the passive ignorance.

16
00:01:47,992 --> 00:01:49,754
We often see this in our daily life.

17
00:01:50,545 --> 00:01:52,108
The TV suddenly goes funny.

18
00:01:52,308 --> 00:01:54,853
We haven't a clue how a TV works or why it's gone funny.

19
00:01:55,596 --> 00:02:02,049
But since we can't get someone to service it, we'll mess about with the knobs, and even lead ourselves to believing that a thump to the casing might work.

20
00:02:03,591 --> 00:02:07,740
No wonder the first words of the exasperated service person is, Who's been messing about with this?

21
00:02:08,582 --> 00:02:10,646
We, of course, adopt a posture of innocent ignorance.

22
00:02:12,009 --> 00:02:19,419
More seriously, in earlier times when people were really exasperated with disasters such as floods, famines, droughts, suddenly gods needed to be appeased.

23
00:02:20,061 --> 00:02:21,984
Animal and human sacrifice is called for.

24
00:02:23,966 --> 00:02:28,292
The great problem with delusion and its manifestations is that we don't know we're deluded.

25
00:02:28,752 --> 00:02:31,116
This is by definition the meaning of delusion, I know.

26
00:02:32,276 --> 00:02:35,961
In mental illness, the problem with the paranoid person is that he has no insight.

27
00:02:36,520 --> 00:02:39,805
He doesn't realize in any way that his thinking does not match reality.

28
00:02:40,544 --> 00:02:46,692
And no matter how much you say it to him, or show him, or try to make it obvious to him, yet his disturbed thinking persists.

29
00:02:47,412 --> 00:02:48,674
Delusions are rock hard.

30
00:02:51,036 --> 00:02:55,461
Now this ignorance delusion is the fount of two other manifestations.

31
00:02:56,161 --> 00:02:57,522
Desire and hatred.

32
00:02:58,604 --> 00:03:01,727
Desire here always refers to sensual desire.

33
00:03:02,770 --> 00:03:08,981
It is first of all believing that life is about sensual indulgence, and secondly that happiness is to be found in sense pleasure.

34
00:03:10,283 --> 00:03:11,986
This is what constitutes the delusion.

35
00:03:12,908 --> 00:03:14,391
Herein is our great confusion.

36
00:03:14,872 --> 00:03:24,069
We, as human beings, have five senses which respond to the world, and through which we enjoy a lot of pleasure, be it food, lovely sights, the feeling of a sea breeze, or sexual pleasures.

37
00:03:24,943 --> 00:03:33,092
Even within the mind itself, the sixth sense in Buddhism, there is great pleasure to be had in fantasies and mental states of excitement, infatuation and so on.

38
00:03:33,813 --> 00:03:37,798
In fact, for most of us, a lot of the time, life can be very pleasurable.

39
00:03:38,838 --> 00:03:42,962
Our technological society goes out of its way to try and turn this life into a sensual delight.

40
00:03:43,524 --> 00:03:50,091
From compact discs, TVs, jacuzzis, you name it, there is some machine somewhere to heighten our sensual experience.

41
00:03:51,961 --> 00:03:54,965
Unfortunately, pleasure has an inbuilt obsolescence.

42
00:03:55,806 --> 00:04:01,955
No matter how wonderful, how exciting our pleasurable experience is, there comes a time when we tire of it, we get bored.

43
00:04:03,015 --> 00:04:11,307
So now this desire, which has caused us to find pleasure with its attendant emotional highs, drives us on to seek more and more pleasure.

44
00:04:12,269 --> 00:04:21,141
If we watch ourselves closely throughout the day, we will see how tireless we are in trying to make ourselves comfortable and to enjoy some sort of new pleasure all the time.

45
00:04:22,149 --> 00:04:24,312
As soon as I write, I think, cup of tea.

46
00:04:24,892 --> 00:04:27,255
At breakfast, it's, what new cereal have I?

47
00:04:28,257 --> 00:04:30,379
Work is boring, I need to look for something interesting.

48
00:04:31,021 --> 00:04:32,723
TV is boring, I need to call a friend.

49
00:04:33,603 --> 00:04:34,704
What am I going to do this evening?

50
00:04:34,785 --> 00:04:36,067
Oh, disaster, I've got nothing on.

51
00:04:37,228 --> 00:04:39,110
Can you imagine a weekend with nothing to do?

52
00:04:40,312 --> 00:04:44,497
For others who lead stressful, busy lives, they may look forward to a weekend of nothing to do.

53
00:04:44,978 --> 00:04:47,600
If something turns up they have to do, they're very unhappy.

54
00:04:48,812 --> 00:04:54,059
When we see this merry-go-round desire forces us to ride, we realize there is no end to the demand.

55
00:04:55,199 --> 00:04:59,244
We desire this, this gets boring, so we want that, and so on.

56
00:05:00,264 --> 00:05:07,192
The search for pleasure can never end, for desire itself, as a disposition of mind, can never be fully satisfied.

57
00:05:09,654 --> 00:05:14,319
This, however, is only the surface of things, for underneath the merry-go-round sits fear and anxiety.

58
00:05:15,081 --> 00:05:18,685
The more we attach to our pleasure, the more we define ourselves by it.

59
00:05:19,204 --> 00:05:24,014
This self-definition with pleasure and pleasurable emotions and feelings is the ultimate delusion.

60
00:05:24,815 --> 00:05:25,437
I have a job.

61
00:05:25,937 --> 00:05:27,139
It gives me wealth and status.

62
00:05:27,480 --> 00:05:29,524
When I walk the streets, I can hold myself high.

63
00:05:30,286 --> 00:05:32,470
I'm a prime minister, a nurse, a bus driver, a teacher.

64
00:05:33,391 --> 00:05:37,579
It doesn't matter what it is, so long as I identify with it, so long as I say, that's me.

65
00:05:39,423 --> 00:05:40,384
Suddenly I lose my job.

66
00:05:40,865 --> 00:05:41,567
Now what am I?

67
00:05:42,610 --> 00:05:45,394
No wonder people go into severe depression when they're made redundant.

68
00:05:46,334 --> 00:05:49,139
To be made redundant is to rip one's badge off.

69
00:05:49,160 --> 00:05:49,980
It's to denude them.

70
00:05:50,120 --> 00:05:55,267
It's to say, that person thought she was a prime minister, nurse, bus driver or teacher, but in fact she's not.

71
00:05:56,771 --> 00:06:00,636
These job definitions aren't as in any essential way or real way at all.

72
00:06:01,637 --> 00:06:02,379
But we think they are.

73
00:06:02,519 --> 00:06:03,300
That's the delusion.

74
00:06:04,141 --> 00:06:06,745
That's why it causes us so much suffering to lose our jobs.

75
00:06:07,670 --> 00:06:12,817
As if the drop in standard of living were not suffering enough, we compound it with loss of self-esteem and confidence.

76
00:06:13,798 --> 00:06:21,048
Even when we know our redundancy is not caused by our bad work or unpunctuality or anything like that, we react with depression, anxiety and so on.

77
00:06:22,449 --> 00:06:33,423
When we realise the connection between pleasure and identity, between pleasure and the fear of loss of pleasure, then at least we can begin to look for another way of looking at life, which won't cause us to suffer.

78
00:06:35,158 --> 00:06:40,403
In order to find out how we can undermine our personal suffering, we need to observe ourselves in daily life.

79
00:06:41,064 --> 00:06:44,586
We need to question our attitudes, all our greeds, as opposed to needs.

80
00:06:45,168 --> 00:06:46,408
See what stands up to reason.

81
00:06:48,071 --> 00:06:50,872
If my father comes home from the pub with a black eye, I'm furious.

82
00:06:51,374 --> 00:06:53,115
I go to the pub, I want to know how it happened.

83
00:06:53,535 --> 00:06:55,836
I want the attacker punished, I'm very angry, I'm very upset.

84
00:06:56,778 --> 00:07:00,762
If Jimmy, the neighbour I argued with last week, gets beaten up, I think he deserves it.

85
00:07:01,262 --> 00:07:03,124
It serves him right, he was asking for it.

86
00:07:04,403 --> 00:07:06,026
If my car is stolen, it's a shock.

87
00:07:06,406 --> 00:07:07,067
My car.

88
00:07:07,548 --> 00:07:08,889
How can I live without my car?

89
00:07:09,290 --> 00:07:10,773
I'm full of hatred toward the thieves.

90
00:07:11,593 --> 00:07:16,963
I find no peace of mind until my car is restored to me and the insurance paid are the thieves brought to justice.

91
00:07:18,064 --> 00:07:23,173
When my next-door neighbor's car is stolen, I'm full of commiseration about the rottenness of the world today.

92
00:07:23,692 --> 00:07:24,153
No shock.

93
00:07:24,435 --> 00:07:24,875
No anger.

94
00:07:25,235 --> 00:07:26,076
I don't feel depressed.

95
00:07:26,398 --> 00:07:26,918
Why should I?

96
00:07:27,079 --> 00:07:27,879
It's not my car.

97
00:07:29,682 --> 00:07:33,267
This is what the Buddha meant when he talked of desire and all its ramifications.

98
00:07:33,988 --> 00:07:43,944
Desire arises out of a particular delusion that somehow our happiness rests on the quantity and quality of sensual pleasure and the emotional delights it creates.

99
00:07:45,627 --> 00:07:49,735
This delusion sits on, arises out of, that fundamental ignorance of not knowing.

100
00:07:50,495 --> 00:07:56,466
This delusion sits on the fundamental ignorance of not knowing where we are to find our ultimate happiness.

101
00:07:57,019 --> 00:08:09,154
This ignorance, this delusion, this desire, create craving for things, and so life is a continual finding satisfaction, now here, now there, and with no rest, no permanent satisfaction at all.

102
00:08:11,918 --> 00:08:15,704
It's good practice to listen to ourselves and write down the words of desire we use.

103
00:08:16,124 --> 00:08:18,286
I want, I wish, I would like, and so on.

104
00:08:19,148 --> 00:08:21,630
Next to see how we use these words of obsession.

105
00:08:22,673 --> 00:08:26,858
I have to, I must, I need, I should, I ought, and so on.

106
00:08:27,665 --> 00:08:33,918
Then to make two lists of those things we desire and those things we think we need and see how many are realistic.

107
00:08:34,940 --> 00:08:37,806
Of course I need to eat, but do I need to go to a restaurant?

108
00:08:39,710 --> 00:08:44,440
When we become more aware of how we use these words we become more aware of our attachments and obsessions.

109
00:08:45,181 --> 00:08:48,086
The way we use our language reveals our delusions.

110
00:08:49,011 --> 00:08:53,839
It's a good practice to make this list and really question what is need as opposed to greed.

111
00:08:54,419 --> 00:08:57,605
It surprises us to find how little we do actually need.

112
00:08:58,767 --> 00:09:01,772
The Buddha wanted to reduce the monk's needs to the absolute basics.

113
00:09:02,172 --> 00:09:03,634
He called these the four requisites.

114
00:09:04,375 --> 00:09:06,619
Food, clothing, shelter and medicine.

115
00:09:07,299 --> 00:09:13,369
And in each case the rules go to show that it is only the basic rudimentary kind of these four requisites that is sufficient.

116
00:09:14,191 --> 00:09:17,095
Sufficient meaning what is actually needed.

117
00:09:18,931 --> 00:09:21,836
This came home to me once when I attended a meditation course in India.

118
00:09:22,297 --> 00:09:29,691
The food for the three weeks I was there was simply chapati, a flat, unleavened whole wheat bread, and dal, or lentil soup.

119
00:09:29,711 --> 00:09:32,956
Now and again I got other vegetables and fruit, but in no way consistently.

120
00:09:34,472 --> 00:09:36,895
It was only three weeks, but I remember how worried I became.

121
00:09:37,275 --> 00:09:39,919
I thought my body would fall apart for lack of proteins and vitamins.

122
00:09:40,721 --> 00:09:44,004
In fact, I never felt healthier, and people remarked on how healthy I looked.

123
00:09:44,765 --> 00:09:48,470
It made me realize all the fears and obsessions I had about food.

124
00:09:49,471 --> 00:09:51,914
Such fears and obsessions caused me suffering.

125
00:09:55,018 --> 00:10:02,067
So here we have the deluded human being, thinking that sense pleasure are the be-all and end-all of life.

126
00:10:02,467 --> 00:10:03,349
This is hedonism.

127
00:10:04,110 --> 00:10:08,977
Such a person who really thinks that pleasure is the greatest good is a hedonist.

128
00:10:10,360 --> 00:10:21,938
But in reality, this pleasure, this greatest good, is a wild goose chase, running after this only to find boredom, running after that only to find dissatisfaction, disillusionment, and so on and so on.

129
00:10:22,701 --> 00:10:27,327
But worse, when we move from one pleasure to another, we want it to be better.

130
00:10:27,595 --> 00:10:32,380
We don't want films to continue, the same old cowboy film with the same old plot.

131
00:10:32,701 --> 00:10:35,063
We want it to be different, more spills and more thrills.

132
00:10:36,044 --> 00:10:43,153
So the old cowboy movie becomes a sexy musical, or a realistic Sam Peckinpah film showing bullets exploding out of cowboy chests.

133
00:10:44,615 --> 00:10:46,197
The horror movie of yesterday makes us laugh.

134
00:10:46,277 --> 00:10:47,658
We want real horror, real terror.

135
00:10:48,399 --> 00:10:51,023
Love stories have to have desperate twists and turns.

136
00:10:52,124 --> 00:10:55,628
And if this is true of the movies, how much truer it is of our own lives.

137
00:10:56,451 --> 00:10:57,913
We so much want to be in the movies.

138
00:10:58,313 --> 00:11:02,019
We so much want to emulate the film stars, be heroine, hero, whatever.

139
00:11:02,759 --> 00:11:03,721
We have to succeed.

140
00:11:04,302 --> 00:11:13,653
But this success, especially in our greatly materialistic Western civilization, is measured simply by how much pleasure we can buy, be it consumer goods or services.

141
00:11:14,553 --> 00:11:15,615
Last week I went to Spain.

142
00:11:16,517 --> 00:11:17,999
This year I'm going to China, don't you know?

143
00:11:18,799 --> 00:11:20,822
Next year I've booked on a spaceship to Mars.

144
00:11:23,501 --> 00:11:28,687
Now this delusive desire has established an identity, and this identity is what I call me.

145
00:11:29,669 --> 00:11:31,751
As far as I am concerned, I am what I want.

146
00:11:32,413 --> 00:11:33,234
I am what I have.

147
00:11:33,914 --> 00:11:35,496
I am the satisfaction of my desires.

148
00:11:36,217 --> 00:11:39,621
And through this me, I define and identify what is mine.

149
00:11:40,523 --> 00:11:43,186
If I lose what is mine, I also lose a bit of me.

150
00:11:43,225 --> 00:11:47,831
And that is when this I reacts with anger or depression or fear or what have you.

151
00:11:48,673 --> 00:11:52,918
In extreme cases, this I thinks it will go mad or even lose the desire to live.

152
00:11:53,775 --> 00:12:00,447
When we are at the point of to be or not to be, we are at the second and third type of desire the Buddha talked of.

153
00:12:02,331 --> 00:12:08,763
The desire to be, in this sense, is really the desire to become, to keep on renewing life, to keep on living.

154
00:12:10,005 --> 00:12:17,860
Whenever death comes near, either by way of the loss of a dear one, or a life-threatening illness to our own person, great horror arises.

155
00:12:18,682 --> 00:12:26,756
Essentially, the terror we feel now at the possible loss of life is no different from the fear or anxiety we feel if our jobs are threatened or loved ones leave us.

156
00:12:28,320 --> 00:12:36,013
The quantity of terror, fear, anxiety we feel is the measure of our identity with the loved one, the job, this myself.

157
00:12:37,034 --> 00:12:38,817
And yet we know we will die.

158
00:12:39,743 --> 00:12:42,447
We know very well we will grow old and die.

159
00:12:42,667 --> 00:12:43,548
We know it very well.

160
00:12:44,428 --> 00:12:50,157
There is undeniable evidence that everyone else, even my loved ones, will die, will grow old and die.

161
00:12:51,139 --> 00:12:53,581
But even though we know it, we don't seem to really accept it.

162
00:12:54,342 --> 00:13:00,991
There's something in us that keeps blinding us to the fact, and we carry on behaving as if it happens to everyone else, but not to us.

163
00:13:02,068 --> 00:13:03,250
how deep our delusion is.

164
00:13:04,232 --> 00:13:14,350
So much so, that because we can't face the death of myself, we create all sorts of heavens where we shall be able to enjoy the pleasures of life, transitory fleeting pleasures, mind, for eternity.

165
00:13:15,933 --> 00:13:18,457
Here, then, is the fallacy of eternalism.

166
00:13:19,044 --> 00:13:23,549
Whatever is eternal cannot in itself be fleeting, it cannot in itself change.

167
00:13:24,471 --> 00:13:39,426
And yet such is our inability to conceive of a life that is not transitory, and therefore nothing to do with fleeting pleasures, that we create happy hunting grounds, eternal realms, everlasting heavens, where we can eat forever, or drink forever, or have any pleasure you care to name, forever.

168
00:13:40,827 --> 00:13:47,634
This is eternalism, the belief that the same person carries on in the same way, but perfectly happily, after death.

169
00:13:47,902 --> 00:13:49,744
It is but an extended hedonism.

170
00:13:50,784 --> 00:13:54,429
But what we really see here is the problem of ignorance and delusion.

171
00:13:55,150 --> 00:13:56,831
Delusion cannot see beyond itself.

172
00:13:57,393 --> 00:14:06,062
It has no other option but to recreate itself, even though all the time the feedback is saying, no, this doesn't last, this isn't permanent.

173
00:14:07,043 --> 00:14:16,895
Even though experience tells us pleasure, the search for pleasure, the dependency on pleasure, only accumulates worry, obsession, anxiety, frustration, depression, and worse.

174
00:14:19,457 --> 00:14:26,227
Now when I fail to achieve the great pleasured Rome, then awful feelings of inadequacy arise, a loss of self-esteem.

175
00:14:26,989 --> 00:14:28,631
In my depression I face this horror.

176
00:14:29,413 --> 00:14:35,020
Realizing that in fact pleasure does not deliver the permanent good, I see only death, only annihilation.

177
00:14:35,923 --> 00:14:39,769
In my despair I believe death will bring some total ending, a permanent relief.

178
00:14:40,909 --> 00:14:44,335
Even in ordinary life, if thing gets too much, I run away.

179
00:14:45,236 --> 00:14:48,081
If a relationship gets too hard, I divorce.

180
00:14:48,279 --> 00:14:50,264
If the job gets too much, I change.

181
00:14:50,804 --> 00:14:52,147
If I'm unhappy, I go to bed.

182
00:14:52,508 --> 00:14:54,250
I annihilate myself in sweet sleep.

183
00:14:55,592 --> 00:14:58,538
When pain and suffering arises, the desire to get rid of it arises.

184
00:14:59,640 --> 00:15:04,129
This is the twin to desire, aversion, the desire to do away with what is painful.

185
00:15:04,990 --> 00:15:07,554
If I want pleasure, I don't want pain.

186
00:15:08,480 --> 00:15:19,118
Aversion is just the negative side of desire, and this in its extreme delusive form produces the escape mentality, the running away, at worst, from oneself by killing oneself.

187
00:15:20,581 --> 00:15:23,446
From life by suicide, death ends all.

188
00:15:24,067 --> 00:15:26,110
This is the annihilationist.

189
00:15:26,129 --> 00:15:33,643
Believing in annihilation at death is the logical outcome of believing that human life is only about sensual pleasure, and that it will end.

190
00:15:35,361 --> 00:15:36,243
So where have we got to?

191
00:15:37,345 --> 00:15:46,076
We've said that because of our fundamental ignorance, the not knowing what suffering is, nor the cause of it, nor how to put an end to it, we've produced solutions.

192
00:15:47,037 --> 00:15:50,861
Since these solutions are based on wrong understanding, our delusions are born.

193
00:15:51,923 --> 00:15:58,272
Because we want to be happy, desire arises and we attach to what gives us immediate gratification, our sense pleasures.

194
00:15:59,273 --> 00:16:03,158
The mistake is then made of believing that that is what we really are.

195
00:16:03,307 --> 00:16:06,491
When pleasures fail us, we are thrown into an identity crisis.

196
00:16:07,113 --> 00:16:15,905
Faced with disease, old age and death, we either believe we will be able to take it up again in some heavenly plane forever, or we will all annihilate into nothingness.

197
00:16:18,450 --> 00:16:21,615
In meditation, this merry-go-round should become more and more obvious to us.

198
00:16:22,154 --> 00:16:32,571
All sorts of emotional states and fantasies assail us, some highly pleasurable, some painful, some full of hate and fear and sorrow, and others full of excitement, sentimentality and delight.

199
00:16:33,529 --> 00:16:39,256
all sorts of mental states with their accompaniment of daydream and internal dialogue, films indeed.

200
00:16:40,339 --> 00:16:43,582
But in meditation, our work is to become the detached observer.

201
00:16:44,524 --> 00:16:50,110
We must begin to take a side seat from which we can be attentive to every passing conscious moment.

202
00:16:51,192 --> 00:16:58,861
Whatever the object of our meditation, be it good, bad, painful, pleasurable, no matter, whatever the object, we watch it with keen attentiveness.

203
00:17:00,023 --> 00:17:05,207
All that happens in our mind is to be considered so much phenomena, mental things.

204
00:17:06,587 --> 00:17:13,858
As we come to know, perhaps for the first time in our lives, how much our mind is filled with desires and aversions, insight begins to arise.

205
00:17:14,740 --> 00:17:16,041
Just look at all this stuff.

206
00:17:16,782 --> 00:17:17,884
It really is suffering.

207
00:17:18,405 --> 00:17:20,669
It is just coming up and I've no control over it.

208
00:17:21,230 --> 00:17:35,211
All these desires, these wants, these obsessions, all these petty dislikes, hatreds, grudges, all these self-definitions, self-identifications, opinions, beliefs, criticisms, they're all a source of suffering for me.

209
00:17:35,426 --> 00:17:39,631
Then the question arises, can I live without desire and attachment?

210
00:17:40,152 --> 00:17:42,193
Can I live without aversion and hatred?

211
00:17:42,994 --> 00:17:52,005
Can I live without continually reconditioning myself to look at life as if it was one huge birthday cake for me, for me and no one else?

212
00:17:54,186 --> 00:17:56,229
With these thoughts we move into daily life.

213
00:17:57,230 --> 00:18:04,657
We begin to question all these little people in our head shouting at us, I want this, I need that, I can't live without this, I may as well kill myself if I don't get that.

214
00:18:07,337 --> 00:18:15,547
By questioning our desires and aversions, by seeing them for what they really are, we begin to discover the path that leads out of all this mess.

215
00:18:16,067 --> 00:18:17,929
And this is exactly what the Buddha did himself.

216
00:18:18,970 --> 00:18:25,497
Realizing that no amount of pleasure was ever going to satisfy him, he set out to discover the path that leads out of suffering.

217
00:18:26,637 --> 00:18:29,560
But before he could discover the path, he had to discover the cause.

218
00:18:30,402 --> 00:18:35,067
Remember, the Dharma, the teaching of the Buddha, is not a pill to be taken every morning.

219
00:18:36,598 --> 00:18:40,403
It's a handbook, a guide, which we ourselves have to put into practice.

220
00:18:41,625 --> 00:18:49,496
Discovering that desire for sensual pleasure is not something we should indulge is at first painful, but I like my beer, I like my food.

221
00:18:50,616 --> 00:19:05,896
But as we come to let go of our obsessive, grasping natures, we will discover a kinder nature, one of peace, a nature that does not feed off grasping and expectation, but allows generosity and sits squarely balanced in reality.

222
00:19:07,243 --> 00:19:14,035
a nature no longer pushed about by internal compulsions, but free to respond to others with love and care.

223
00:19:15,217 --> 00:19:17,721
It all leads to a greater satisfaction with our lives.

224
00:19:18,742 --> 00:19:25,333
All we need to do is get to know these desires and aversions and to see them for what they really are.

225
00:19:26,034 --> 00:19:30,622
They pretend to lead us to happiness, but in fact they are wolves in sheep's clothing.

226
00:19:31,722 --> 00:19:34,567
They will lead nowhere but to unhappiness.

227
00:19:35,172 --> 00:19:38,517
Here is the power of meditation, vipassana insight meditation.

228
00:19:39,458 --> 00:19:42,102
It helps us see these mental states for what they really are.

229
00:19:43,384 --> 00:19:46,126
In daily life we need to activate these insights.

230
00:19:46,887 --> 00:19:50,913
We mustn't allow ourselves to get caught up in greed, hatred and delusion.

231
00:19:51,674 --> 00:19:54,077
We must undermine every greed, every hatred.

232
00:19:54,719 --> 00:20:00,166
We must question every opinion and belief in case they are deluded, not simply act upon their command.

233
00:20:00,973 --> 00:20:06,105
We must discover for ourselves what is good, what is right, what leads to happiness and peace.

234
00:20:06,987 --> 00:20:10,815
To happiness and peace of ourselves and all beings.

235
00:20:13,902 --> 00:20:16,386
I hope you found this talk interesting and helpful.

236
00:20:17,288 --> 00:20:19,252
May all of you be happy and peaceful.

